  - name: Mesozoic
    explanation: |
      The Mesozoic Era, spanning approximately 252 to 66 million years ago, occupies a
      critical interval within the Phanerozoic Eon, situated stratigraphically between
      the Paleozoic and the Cenozoic eras. Derived from the Greek μέσος (mesos,
      “middle”) and ζωή (zoē, “life”), the term reflects its position as the “middle
      life” era, following the Paleozoic (“ancient life”) and preceding the Cenozoic
      (“recent life”). This era is subdivided into three periods: the Triassic,
      Jurassic, and Cretaceous, each characterized by distinct biotic and tectonic
      developments.  Geologically, the Mesozoic corresponds with the breakup of the
      supercontinent Pangaea, initiating significant plate tectonic reconfigurations
      evident in stratigraphic sequences worldwide. This breakup facilitated diverse
      depositional environments, evidenced by the widespread occurrence of marine
      limestones and terrestrial red beds, as well as extensive volcanic sequences
      signaling rifting events. These stratigraphic markers enable refined
      correlations and paleoenvironmental reconstructions.  Paleontologically, the
      Mesozoic is renowned for the radiation of dinosaurs, early mammals, and the
      first birds, alongside major marine reptile and invertebrate faunas. Its
      terminal Cretaceous extinction event, widely linked to an asteroid impact and
      volcanism, marks a pivotal biotic turnover that profoundly shaped ensuing
      evolutionary trajectories. Thus, the Mesozoic remains fundamental for
      understanding macroevolutionary patterns, paleoclimatic shifts, and the
      interplay of tectonics and life through deep time.
