        characteristic of its upper stratigraphic layers, particularly prominent in
        European formations such as the White Cliffs of Dover. These deposits result
        from the proliferation of calcareous nanoplankton, notably coccolithophores,
        indicating elevated marine productivity and significant global carbonate
        accumulation.  Stratigraphically, the Cretaceous is delineated between the
        Jurassic period below and the Paleogene period above, marked by a major
        biostratigraphic boundary across the Cretaceous-Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction
        event. This boundary is characterized by a distinctive iridium anomaly and
        widespread sedimentary disruptions, reflective of a catastrophic bolide impact.
        The Cretaceous encompassed substantial tectonic reorganizations, including the
        continued breakup of Pangaea and associated sea-level fluctuations that fostered
        widespread epicontinental seas, facilitating diverse marine and terrestrial
        faunal assemblages.  The Cretaceous period holds critical importance in
        geosciences as it witnessed significant evolutionary milestones, including the
        diversification of angiosperms, the dominance of dinosaurs, and the
        establishment of modern vertebrate clades. Additionally, its sedimentary and
        fossil records provide invaluable insights into paleoenvironmental conditions,
        biotic responses to climatic shifts, and mass extinction dynamics, making it a
        focal interval for studies in stratigraphy, sedimentology, and evolutionary
        biology.
