            undulatoplicatus*.  Stratigraphically, the Turonian interval is characterized by
            widespread marine transgressions resulting in expanded epicontinental seas,
            notably the highstand of the Western Interior Seaway in North America. This
            interval exhibits distinctive calcareous plankton assemblages, including
            inoceramid bivalves and diverse ammonite faunas, which provide biostratigraphic
            resolution essential for regional and global correlation. Additionally, the
            Turonian witnessed significant climatic and oceanographic conditions, with
            evidence of one of the warmest intervals of the Cretaceous, including episodes
            of oceanic anoxia (OAE2 residual effects), which influenced marine biodiversity
            and organic carbon burial.  The Turonian stage is integral to understanding mid-
            Cretaceous paleoecology and paleoclimate due to its role in marine transgression
            dynamics, biotic turnover, and sedimentological records. It bridges the
            Cenomanian biotic expansions and the later Coniacian cooling and faunal shifts,
            offering insights into evolutionary patterns and environmental perturbations
