      - name: Middle
        explanation: |
          The term "Middle" is applied within geologic time divisions primarily as a
          formal or informal subdivision of broader epochs or periods, designating an
          intermediate interval between recognized early and late subdivisions. Its
          etymology stems straightforwardly from its position within a tripartite temporal
          framework, reflecting a middle phase in sedimentation, faunal assemblages, or
          tectonostratigraphic evolution. Although "Middle" is most familiarly encountered
          in epochs such as the Middle Jurassic or Middle Devonian, the concept is broadly
          utilized wherever finer temporal resolution is required beyond binary
          subdivisions.  Chronologically, the "Middle" epoch typically spans several
          million years, bracketed by well-defined boundaries based on biostratigraphic
          markers, isotopic signatures, or lithostratigraphic changes. For instance, the
          Middle Jurassic extends approximately from 174 to 163 million years ago, falling
          between the Early and Late Jurassic epochs. The stratigraphic context of a
          "Middle" interval is often characterized by significant evolutionary radiations,
          climatic shifts, or notable sedimentological transitions, thus serving as a
          crucial reference point for correlating lithologic units and fossil assemblages
          globally.  The designation of a "Middle" stage is essential for elucidating
          patterns of biotic turnover, paleoenvironmental dynamics, and geodynamic
          processes within a refined temporal framework. This facilitates precise
          correlation in regional and global stratigraphy, enabling more accurate
          reconstructions of Earth’s history and evolutionary trajectories. Consequently,
          the "Middle" epoch represents a fundamental component in the chronostratigraphic
          hierarchy, bridging gaps between broader temporal units and enriching our
          understanding of geologic and paleobiologic continuity.
