            significance of Alpine Triassic sequences in global stratigraphy.
            Stratigraphically, the Ladinian is well-defined by a combination of
            biostratigraphic markers, particularly ammonoid zonation, along with conodont
            and palynological data, which provide tight temporal constraints and enable
            global correlation. Its base is conventionally placed near the first appearance
            of the ammonoid genus *Eoprotrachyceras*, while the top coincides with the
            earliest appearance of the genus *Daxatina*. The stage records considerable
            evolutionary radiation following the Permian-Triassic mass extinction, including
            diversification among marine invertebrates such as ammonoids and marine
            reptiles, as well as important terrestrial faunal assemblages.  The Ladinian is
            pivotal for understanding Middle Triassic recovery dynamics and
            paleoenvironmental changes, including oceanic anoxia events and carbonate
            platform evolution. Furthermore, it offers valuable insights into early Mesozoic
            paleogeography and tectonics, reflecting the progressive fragmentation of the
            supercontinent Pangaea. Consequently, the Ladinian stage is a cornerstone
            interval for reconstructing Triassic ecosystems and major evolutionary
            trajectories.
