            interval during the early recovery and diversification following the end-Permian
            mass extinction. The stage is named after the Anisus River (modern Enns River)
            in Austria, reflecting its type locality in the Alpine region where
            characteristic stratotypes and fauna were first described.  Stratigraphically,
            the Anisian is defined by biostratigraphic markers including ammonoid zones,
            notably those dominated by genera such as Ceratites and Gyronites. Its
            deposition spans diverse paleoenvironments, from widespread marine carbonate
            platforms to more restricted siliciclastic basins, offering essential insights
            into Triassic basin evolution and palaeoecological dynamics. The Anisian
            correlates with significant lithostratigraphic units across Tethyan realms and
            other Pangean margins, facilitating global chronostratigraphic integration.
            From a palaeontological perspective, the Anisian documents critical evolutionary
            recovery phases of marine ecosystems, including the radiation of early Mesozoic
            marine reptiles and diverse invertebrate faunas. This stage thus provides a
            vital framework for understanding biotic resilience and the re-establishment of
            ecological complexity during the Triassic, underpinning models of post-
            extinction recovery and environmental shifts following the most severe
