            characterized. The Induan marks a critical interval in Earth’s history,
            coinciding with the aftermath of the most severe mass extinction event—the end-
            Permian extinction—which eradicated an estimated 90–96% of marine species and
            significantly depopulated terrestrial ecosystems.  Stratigraphically, the Induan
            lies at the base of the Triassic, overlying the Changhsingian stage of the late
            Permian and succeeded by the Olenekian. It is most commonly identified through
            biostratigraphic markers such as the first appearances of early Triassic
            ammonoids (e.g., genera such as *Otoceras*) and conodont assemblages that
            reflect a rapid but protracted ecosystem recovery. The Induan is subdivided into
            two substages: the Griesbachian and Dienerian, which enable more refined
            correlation of global sedimentary sequences.  The significance of the Induan
            stage lies in its encapsulation of the initial evolutionary rebound following
            the Permian extinction, documenting both biotic crises and early recovery
            dynamics. The paleoenvironmental and sedimentological records during the Induan
            afford critical insights into how Earth systems and life adapted to extreme
            perturbations, thereby informing models of resilience, extinction selectivity,
