  - name: Paleozoic
    explanation: |
      The Paleozoic Era, derived from the Greek παλαιός (palaios, “ancient”) and ζωή
      (zōē, “life”), denotes the “ancient life” era, reflecting its significance in
      the early diversification of complex multicellular organisms. Spanning
      approximately 541 to 252 million years ago, it constitutes the earliest of the
      three Phanerozoic eon eras, preceding the Mesozoic and Cenozoic.
      Stratigraphically, the Paleozoic is subdivided into six periods: Cambrian,
      Ordovician, Silurian, Devonian, Carboniferous (Mississippian and Pennsylvanian
      in North America), and Permian. These subdivisions correspond to major biotic
      radiations and extinctions that define its internal stratigraphy.  Paleozoic
      stratigraphy is notable for the Cambrian Explosion, a rapid diversification of
      metazoan phyla evidenced by exceptional fossil Lagerstätten, and the
      establishment of complex ecological networks. The era witnessed the colonization
      of terrestrial environments by plants and arthropods during the Silurian and
      Devonian, culminating in the rise of tetrapods. Additionally, extensive marine
      carbonate platforms and terrestrial coal swamps provide critical
      paleoenvironmental proxies. The terminal Permian mass extinction, the most
      severe biotic crisis recorded, marks the Paleozoic’s abrupt end, profoundly
      influencing subsequent biosphere evolution. Understanding Paleozoic stratigraphy
      and biotic events is foundational for reconstructing early Phanerozoic life’s
      trajectory, paleoclimate dynamics, and tectonostratigraphic frameworks pivotal
      for resource exploration and evolutionary biology.
