    - name: Permian
      explanation: |
        The Permian period, spanning approximately 298.9 to 251.9 million years ago,
        marks the final interval of the Paleozoic Era. Its name derives from the
        historic region of Perm in Russia, where early 19th-century stratigraphic
        studies by geologist Sir Roderick Murchison identified distinctive sedimentary
        sequences now globally correlated to this period. Stratigraphically, the Permian
        follows the Carboniferous and precedes the Triassic of the Mesozoic,
        encapsulating significant lithological and paleontological transitions within
        its three recognized epochs: Cisuralian, Guadalupian, and Lopingian.  The
        Permian is critically important for understanding late Paleozoic Earth systems,
        biotic evolution, and extinction dynamics. It witnessed the assembly of the
        supercontinent Pangea, dramatically altering paleogeographic and climatic
        regimes, which influenced sedimentary facies distributions and faunal
        provincialism. Marine communities evolved markedly with diversification of
        fusulinid foraminifera, ammonoids, and bivalves, whereas terrestrial ecosystems
        saw the proliferation of advanced synapsids, including precursors to mammals.
        Notably, the close of the Permian is demarcated by the Permian-Triassic
        boundary, coinciding with the most severe mass extinction event in Earth's
        history, resulting in profound biotic resets and ecosystem restructuring, which
        continue to shape subsequent evolutionary trajectories.  Thus, the Permian
        period serves as a pivotal focus for multidisciplinary investigations into
        paleoenvironmental perturbations, tectonics, and evolutionary biology, bridging
        the Paleozoic-Mesozoic transition and setting the stage for Mesozoic terrestrial
        and marine diversification.
