          by distinct biostratigraphic assemblages and lithological characteristics.
          Stratigraphically, the Lopingian is critical for delineating the late Paleozoic
          marine and terrestrial environments, capturing substantial faunal turnover
          preceding the Permian-Triassic boundary. The epoch’s sedimentary records
          preserve evidence of diverse marine invertebrates, including fusulinid
          foraminifers and radiolarians, alongside expanding terrestrial vertebrate clades
          reflecting ecological complexity in late Permian ecosystems. Notably, the end-
          Lopingian extinction event represents the most severe biotic crisis in
          Phanerozoic history, eliminating over 90% of marine species and profoundly
          impacting terrestrial biota.  The Lopingian’s significance extends beyond
          stratigraphy, providing a temporal framework for investigating the causes and
          consequences of this mass extinction, including volcanic activity, paleoclimate
          perturbations, and ocean anoxia. Consequently, it serves as a pivotal interval
          for understanding macroevolutionary patterns, ecosystem resilience, and the
          reorganization of Earth’s biosphere during critical intervals of global
