    - name: Carboniferous
      explanation: |
        The Carboniferous Period, spanning approximately 359 to 299 million years ago
        during the late Paleozoic Era, derives its name from the extensive coal-bearing
        strata (“carbo” meaning coal and “ferous” meaning bearing) first systematically
        studied in European Carboniferous basins. The period is subdivided into the
        Mississippian (early Carboniferous) and Pennsylvanian (late Carboniferous)
        epochs in North American stratigraphy, reflecting distinct lithological and
        faunal assemblages. Globally, the Carboniferous marks a critical phase of
        extensive sedimentation in equatorial swampy environments that fostered prolific
        organic accumulation, subsequently forming the major coal deposits foundational
        to the Industrial Revolution and modern energy resources.  Stratigraphically,
        the Carboniferous is characterized by cyclothems—rhythmic alternations of marine
        and nonmarine sediments—reflecting fluctuating eustatic sea levels possibly
        driven by glaciations primarily in the Gondwanan continents. This period also
        witnessed high atmospheric oxygen concentrations, with implications for
        gigantism in arthropods and extensive forest ecosystems dominated by lycopsids,
        ferns, and early gymnosperms. Paleontologically, the Carboniferous is pivotal
        for elucidating the early diversification of amniotes, representing the
        evolutionary divergence toward terrestrial vertebrate lineages.  Understanding
        the Carboniferous is crucial for reconstructing late Paleozoic paleoenvironments
        and biotic responses to climatic shifts, as well as for interpreting sedimentary
        basin architecture and paleoatmospheric conditions that directly influenced
        evolutionary trajectories and coal formation. Its multifaceted impact renders it
        a cornerstone period in geology and paleontology, informing both fundamental
        science and applied resource geology.
