        dominated successions and carbonate platforms, which herald the establishment of
        stable shallow marine environments. It is traditionally subdivided into four
        epochs—Terreneuvian, Series 2, Series 3, and Furongian—capturing crucial
        biostratigraphic intervals marked by the first appearances of diverse trilobite
        taxa, archaeocyathids, and the initial radiation of metazoans with mineralized
        skeletons. The Cambrian is fundamentally important due to the “Cambrian
        Explosion,” a rapid diversification of multicellular life forms, which
        precipitated the establishment of complex ecosystems and nearly all major animal
        phyla. This biotic diversification is recorded in exceptional fossil
        Lagerstätten, such as the Burgess Shale and Chengjiang biotas, providing
        unparalleled insights into early animal morphology, ecology, and evolutionary
        innovation. Consequently, the Cambrian Period is both a temporal and conceptual
        pivot in Earth history, bridging Precambrian microbial-dominated biospheres to
        Phanerozoic animal-dominated marine ecosystems, and remains pivotal for
        understanding the origins and early evolution of complex life.
