- name: Proterozoic
  explanation: |
    The Proterozoic Eon, spanning approximately 2.5 billion to 541 million years
    ago, represents a critical interval in Earth’s geologic history bridging the
    Archean and Phanerozoic eons. The term “Proterozoic,” derived from the Greek
    words *proteron* (former) and *zoe* (life), underscores its characterization as
    a “former life” era, one preceding the proliferation of complex multicellular
    organisms. This eon encompasses three major subdivisions—Paleoproterozoic,
    Mesoproterozoic, and Neoproterozoic—each marked by distinctive tectonic,
    atmospheric, and biological milestones.  Stratigraphically, the Proterozoic is
    distinguished by widespread stabilization of continental cratons, culminating in
    extensive platform sedimentation and major orogenic events, such as the assembly
    and breakup of supercontinents including Columbia and Rodinia. Crucially, this
    eon witnessed the gradual oxygenation of the atmosphere during the Great
    Oxidation Event, profoundly altering redox conditions, mineralogy, and metabolic
    pathways. The Neoproterozoic further recorded severe glaciations, including the
    hypothesized “Snowball Earth” episodes, and the emergence of the earliest known
    metazoans, evidenced by the Ediacaran biota.  The Proterozoic’s significance
    emerges from its role in setting the stage for Phanerozoic biodiversity. It
    encapsulates the transition from microbial dominance to eukaryotic complexity,
    illuminating evolutionary innovations in cell biology, ecology, and
    biogeochemical cycles. For geologists and paleontologists, investigating
    Proterozoic strata offers insights into early life’s environmental constraints
    and the interplay between Earth system processes that shaped the biosphere’s
    trajectory.
  rank: eon
  end_ma: 2500
