  - name: Neoproterozoic
    explanation: |
      The Neoproterozoic Era, spanning from approximately 1,000 to 541 million years
      ago, represents the final subdivision of the Proterozoic Eon and precedes the
      Phanerozoic Eon. The term "Neoproterozoic" derives from the Greek "neo-" meaning
      "new" and "Proterozoic," collectively indicating the "new" or late portion of
      the Proterozoic. This era is subdivided into three periods: the Tonian,
      Cryogenian, and Ediacaran, each characterized by significant geological and
      biological transitions. Stratigraphically, the Neoproterozoic is marked by
      globally distributed sedimentary sequences that bear evidence of dramatic
      climatic fluctuations, including extensive glaciations and the evolution of
      early complex life.  Perhaps its most notable characteristic is the Cryogenian
      period, which hosts the Sturtian and Marinoan glaciations, widely interpreted as
      "Snowball Earth" events, when ice sheets potentially extended to equatorial
      latitudes. These glaciations reshaped global ocean chemistry, sedimentation
      patterns, and biotic evolution. The subsequent Ediacaran period heralds the
      first appearance of large, multicellular, soft-bodied organisms, preserved in
      iconic fossil assemblages. This biotic diversification prefigures the Cambrian
      explosion and provides crucial insights into early animal evolution, ecosystem
      structuring, and the rise of complex life.  The Neoproterozoic thus occupies a
      pivotal position in Earth history, offering a stratigraphic and temporal
      framework to investigate profound climatic perturbations, redox shifts, and
      evolutionary milestones. Its study informs models of Earth system dynamics,
      biological innovation, and the interplay between geosphere and biosphere prior
      to the Paleozoic radiation.
