        The Ediacaran Period, spanning approximately 635 to 541 million years ago,
        represents the terminal interval of the Neoproterozoic Era immediately preceding
        the Cambrian. The name derives from the Ediacara Hills in South Australia, where
        the first well-documented assemblages of distinctive Late Precambrian soft-
        bodied fossils were discovered in the 1940s and 1950s. These fossils, initially
        enigmatic, are now understood as some of the earliest large, complex
        multicellular organisms, marking a profound evolutionary milestone.
        Stratigraphically, the Ediacaran overlies the Cryogenian glaciations and
        terminates at the base of the Cambrian, with its upper boundary defined by the
        first appearance of complex trace fossils associated with early bilaterians.
        The period’s geological context is characterized by widespread shallow marine
        siliciclastic deposits globally, reflecting a postglacial environment with
        relatively low oxygen levels but increasing ecological complexity. Ediacaran
        biota exhibit a unique morphologic repertoire, including frondose, discoidal,
        and quilted forms, many of which do not fit neatly into extant animal phyla,
        suggesting an experimental phase in metazoan evolution preceding the Cambrian
        explosion. The recognition of the Ediacaran as a discrete period in the
        International Chronostratigraphic Chart (established 2004) highlights its
        significance in understanding the evolutionary and environmental transitions
        that paved the way for Cambrian diversification. Thus, it is pivotal for
        reconstructing the origins of animal life and the conditions that enabled the
        emergence of modern ecosystems.
