        “stretch” or “tension,” reflecting the significant tectonic extension and
        rifting events that characterized this interval. Stratigraphically, the Tonian
        follows the Stenian and precedes the Cryogenian period, and it is primarily
        defined by its position below the globally significant Cryogenian glaciations
        and above older Mesoproterozoic strata.  This period is pivotal in Earth history
        due to major geological and biological developments. Tonian strata often record
        the initial breakup of the supercontinent Rodinia, marked by widespread rift
        basins and the generation of substantial passive margin sequences. Such tectonic
        reorganization influenced ocean chemistry and nutrient flux, setting the stage
        for profound evolutionary innovations. Biologically, the Tonian hosts early
        evidence of eukaryotic diversification, including the first putative
        multicellular organisms and embryonic stages of metazoan life, although
        macrofossils remain sparse. Furthermore, isotopic excursions in carbon and
        sulfur during the Tonian suggest substantial environmental and geochemical
        perturbations, underpinning hypotheses regarding the rise of complex life and
        pre-Cryogenian oxygenation events.  Consequently, the Tonian is a critical focus
        for understanding pre-Cambrian Earth system dynamics, the interplay of
        tectonics, climate, and biosphere evolution, and the precursors to the dramatic
        Cryogenian glaciations and Neoproterozoic biotic radiations.
