      role in bridging early crustal genesis and the more biologically dynamic epochs
      that followed.  Geologically, the Mesoarchean is characterized by widespread
      greenstone belt formations and the stabilization of cratonic nuclei. This period
      witnessed intensified processes of continental crustal growth through accretion
      and magmatic activity, evident in granitic plutons and
      tonalite–trondhjemite–granodiorite (TTG) suites preserved in ancient cratons
      such as the Kaapvaal and Pilbara. These lithologies provide pivotal constraints
      on early geodynamic regimes, including potential evidence for the initiation of
      proto-plate tectonics. Sedimentary sequences from this era reveal evolving
      surface environments and the persistence of microbial life, although biomarkers
      remain sparse and equivocal.  The Mesoarchean’s significance lies in its role as
      a critical transitional interval that documents the maturation of Earth’s
      lithosphere and nascent biosphere. Understanding this era enhances
      interpretations of early crustal differentiation processes, atmospheric
      composition evolution, and microbial ecosystem complexity. Consequently, the
      Mesoarchean serves as an indispensable framework for reconstructing Archean
